panels.description: CacheHitRate : Indicates the usage efficiency of the Redis instance. If the cache ratio is lower than about 0.8, it means that a significant amount of keys are evicted, expired, or don't exist. This is calculated using cache_hits and cache_misses statistics in the following way: cache_hits /(cache_hits + cache_misses).
panels.title: Hit Ratio

panels.description: DatabaseMemoryUsagePercentage : Percentage of the memory available for the cluster that is in use. This is calculated using used_memory/maxmemory from Redis INFO
panels.title: DB Mem Usage

panels.description: EngineCPUUtilization 	: Provides CPU utilization of the Redis engine thread. Because Redis is single-threaded, you can use this metric to analyze the load of the Redis process itself. The EngineCPUUtilization metric provides a more precise visibility of the Redis process.
panels.title: CPU Engine Usage

panels.title: Total Items

panels.description: IsMaster : Indicates whether the node is master node of current shard/cluster. The metric can be either 0 (not master) or 1 (master).
panels.title: Masters

panels.description: MasterLinkHealthStatus : This status has two values: 0 or 1. The value 0 indicates that data in the ElastiCache primary node is not in sync with Redis on EC2. The value of 1 indicates that the data is in sync. To complete the migration, use the CompleteMigration API operation.
panels.title: Master Link Health Status

panels.description: EngineCPUUtilization : Provides CPU utilization of the Redis engine thread
panels.title: CPU Engine Usage

panels.description:
DatabaseMemoryUsagePercentage : Percentage of the memory available for the cluster that is in use. This is calculated using used_memory/maxmemory from Redis INFO
.
panels.title: DB Memory Usage

panels.description:
CurrConnections : The number of client connections, excluding connections from read replicas. ElastiCache uses two to four of the connections to monitor the cluster in each case. This is derived from the connected_clients statistic at Redis INFO
.
panels.title: Clients

panels.description: NewConnections : The total number of connections that have been accepted by the server during this period. This is derived from the total_connections_received statistic at Redis INFO
panels.title: New Clients

panels.description: ReplicationBytes : For nodes in a replicated configuration, ReplicationBytes reports the number of bytes that the primary is sending to all of its replicas. This metric is representative of the write load on the replication group. This is derived from the master_repl_offset statistic at Redis INFO
panels.title: Replication Bytes

panels.description: ReplicationLag : This metric is only applicable for a node running as a read replica. It represents how far behind, in seconds, the replica is in applying changes from the primary node. For Redis engine version 5.0.6 onwards, the lag can be measured in milliseconds.
panels.title: Replication Lag

panels.description: SaveInProgress : This binary metric returns 1 whenever a background save (forked or forkless) is in progress, and 0 otherwise. A background save process is typically used during snapshots and syncs. These operations can cause degraded performance. Using the SaveInProgress metric, you can diagnose whether degraded performance was caused by a background save process. This is derived from the rdb_bgsave_in_progress statistic at Redis INFO
panels.title: Save In Progress

panels.description: CacheHitRate : Indicates the usage efficiency of the Redis instance. If the cache ratio is lower than about 0.8, it means that a significant amount of keys are evicted, expired, or don't exist. This is calculated using cache_hits and cache_misses statistics in the following way: cache_hits /(cache_hits + cache_misses).
panels.title: Cache Hit Ratio

panels.description:
CacheHits : The number of successful read-only key lookups in the main dictionary. This is derived from keyspace_hits statistic at Redis.   
CacheMisses : The number of unsuccessful read-only key lookups in the main dictionary. This is derived from keyspace_misses statistic at Redis INFO  
Evictions : The number of keys that have been evicted due to the maxmemory limit. This is derived from the evicted_keys statistic at Redis INFO.  
Reclaimed : The total number of key expiration events. This is derived from the expired_keys statistic at Redis INFO
panels.title: Cache Details

panels.description: CPUUtilization : The percentage of CPU utilization for the entire host.
panels.title: CPU Usage

panels.description: FreeableMemory : The amount of free memory available on the host. This is derived from the RAM, buffers, and cache that the OS reports as freeable.
panels.title: FreeableMemory

panels.description:
SwapUsage : The amount of swap used on the host. This metric should not exceed 50 MB. If it does, see the following topics: 
- Ensuring that you have enough memory to create a Redis snapshot 
https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonElastiCache/latest/red-ug/BestPractices.BGSAVE.html 
- Managing Reserved Memory 
https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonElastiCache/latest/red-ug/redis-memory-management.html
panels.title: Swap Usage

panels.description: NetworkBytesIn : The number of bytes the host has read from the network.
panels.title: Network In

panels.description: NetworkBytesOut : The number of bytes sent out on all network interfaces by the instance.
panels.title: Network Out
